<section class="section section--alt" id="guide-bookkeeping-rates-2026-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">How bookkeeping is actually priced.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Bookkeeping doesn&rsquo;t have a single sticker price, because it isn&rsquo;t a single thing &mdash; it&rsquo;s a body of recurring work whose size depends on your business. In 2026 it&rsquo;s sold three ways. <strong>Hourly</strong> means you pay for time spent: a per-hour rate against however many hours the work takes, so the total isn&rsquo;t known until the invoice arrives. <strong>Fixed-fee</strong> means a single price for a defined piece of work &mdash; a cleanup of a set number of months, a fresh setup, a migration &mdash; agreed before anyone starts. A <strong>monthly retainer</strong> is a flat recurring price for keeping the books current month after month, sized to your volume and what&rsquo;s included.</p>
      <p>The number on any of those quotes is really a function of the <em>work</em>, not the rate. Two businesses can both want &ldquo;monthly bookkeeping&rdquo; and get prices that differ by several times over, because one has ten transactions a month and one bank account while the other has hundreds of transactions, multiple accounts, payroll, and sales tax in three states. So the useful question isn&rsquo;t &ldquo;what&rsquo;s the going rate&rdquo; &mdash; rates vary too much to quote a meaningful national average honestly &mdash; it&rsquo;s &ldquo;what drives <em>my</em> price, and which model puts the risk on the right side of the table.&rdquo; The sections below answer both, then give TechBrot&rsquo;s real ranges as a planning anchor.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

